Problem Statement💊¶

As a Datascientist in a pharmaceutical company 🔬 the goal of this project is to develop a predictive model to determine whether patients have Parkinson's disease 🦠 using a comprehensive dataset. This dataset includes

1)Demographic information🚯, 2)lifestyle factors😷, 3)medical history👨‍⚕️, 4)clinical measurements🏥, 5)cognitive and functional assessments🧫, 6)symptoms🦼, and 8)Diagnosis indicator🧪.

By analyzing this data, the aim is to identify key factors associated with Parkinson's disease and create a reliable prediction tool 🏅. This model will assist healthcare professionals in early detection and intervention, potentially improving patient outcomes💉. Additionally, it will provide valuable insights for researchers studying the disease's progression and its impact☢️.

Test run 8: L2 Regularization (Weight Regularization):- 🌐¶

Experimenting :-L2 regularization penalizes large weights, promoting a simpler model and reducing overfitting, which can improve generalization to unseen data.

In [ ]:
model8 = keras.Sequential([
    keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(33,)),

    keras.layers.Dense(20, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01)),
    # Added L2 regularization

    keras.layers.Dense(2, activation='sigmoid')
])

model8.compile(optimizer='adam',

               loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',

               metrics=['accuracy']
              )

historyNN08 = model8.fit(X_train_std, y_resampled,epochs=20, validation_split=0.1 )

Recall score(TPR) :-¶

📞 Recall score helps here because it helps in finding all relavant cases within a dataset , in disease detection missing positive cases(i.e false negatives) is not acceptable in real world scenario and it might causes major loss to the company.

In [75]:
# Making predictions
y_pred_proba = model8.predict(X_test_std)
y_pred = n.argmax(y_pred_proba, axis=1)

15/15 [==============================] - 0s 1ms/step

recall = recall_score(y_testing, y_pred)
In [77]:

The Recall score of the model is =88.6 percent

Note-our model correctly identifies 88.6% of actual postive cases in our given dataset out of all positive instances.¶

F1_score :-🚀¶

As our dataset is imbalanced as observed earlier,F1 score 🚄 is useful in dealing with imbalanced dataset and gives a metric that balances both precision and recall

In [78]:
f1 = f1_score(y_testing, y_pred)
In [79]:
print(f'The F1 score of the model is ={n.round(f1*100,2)} percent')

The F1 score of the model is =86.38 percent

Note-The F1 score is 86.38% it indicates there is good balance between precision an recall suggesting our model is good in identifying both postive and negative cases.¶

Conclusion ✅¶

🚩 Our Dataset was a imbalanced dataset and we have used Oversampling method(SMOTE) for our validations.

🚩 we have conducted 1 trail run and 10 different test runs with many permutations and combinations for our analysis in that, using L2 Regularization provided best results i.e 83.62% of accuracy score ,88.38 % of Recall score and 86.38% of F1 score.

🚩Limitations - As we choose the model with L2 Regularization it is possible that the model might memorize the data and which can lead to over fitting condition by increasing the complexity of the model increases the model's instability , there might be a requirement of more data to train properly & efficiently and might require further hyperparameter tuning like early stopping , learning rate and using regularization techniques.
